TryHackMe - Networking Basics
Today I learned the fundamentals of networking.
First, what is a network?
A network is two or more devices connected together so they can communicate and share data.
Devices can be connected in two ways:
Wired connections using Ethernet cables.
Wireless connections using technologies such as Wi-Fi and Bluetooth.
What is the Internet?
Before understanding the Internet, we need to understand networks.
Many homes, schools, companies, and organizations have their own networks. These are separate networks.
When many networks are connected together around the world, it forms the Internet.
The Internet is basically a network of networks.
We use the Internet to communicate, share data, access websites, send emails, and connect with systems around the world.
Internet Service Providers (ISP)
To access the Internet, we need an Internet Service Provider (ISP).
Examples include:
Jio
Bharti Airtel
ISPs provide Internet connectivity and assign public IP addresses so our devices can communicate with other networks on the Internet.
IP Addresses
Every device on a network needs an address.
This address is called an IP address.
There are two common types:
Private IP addresses used inside local networks.
Public IP addresses used on the Internet.
Public IP addresses are usually assigned by the ISP.
Ping and ICMP
I also learned about Ping.
Ping uses ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol).
It helps determine whether another device is reachable and measures how long packets take to travel and return.
This measurement is called latency.
MAC Addresses
Every network interface has a unique MAC address.
A MAC address helps identify devices on a local network.
The first part identifies the manufacturer, while the remaining part uniquely identifies the device.
Key Takeaways
A network consists of connected devices.
Devices can communicate through wired or wireless technologies.
The Internet is a network of networks.
ISPs provide Internet connectivity.
IP addresses identify devices on networks.
Ping uses ICMP to test connectivity and latency.
MAC addresses uniquely identify devices on local networks.
This room helped me understand the basic building blocks of networking and how devices communicate across local networks and the Internet.
